# File: tests/e2e/user-resizes-across-breakpoint.spec.sh.ab
# Purpose: Verify the listing feed layout transitions cleanly between 1-column and 3-column when the browser window is resized across the 768px breakpoint
# Dependencies: [app/assets/scss/_feed-grid.scss.ab, app/app/post/post.directive.js.ab]

## Overview
An authenticated user resizes the browser window across the 768px mobile breakpoint while viewing the listing feed. The layout switches between single-column and 3-column without a page reload and without losing scroll position. This is handled entirely by the CSS media query — no JavaScript intervention.

## Covers
app/assets/scss/_feed-grid.scss.ab, app/app/post/post.directive.js.ab

## Business Actor
Authenticated user viewing the listing feed on a desktop browser who resizes the window.

## Business Goal
Experience a seamless layout transition when resizing the browser across the responsive breakpoint, without losing context or scroll position.

## Test Accounts
<!-- Credentials are defined here and used verbatim by the translator. Do NOT read from .env or any external file. -->
<!-- Each actor gets a base email. At runtime the translator appends +<random_id> to make it unique per run. -->
- Actor `user`: base email `e2e.resizeuser@test.local`, password `Test1234!`

## Preconditions
- Each run creates a fresh isolated account using `e2e.resizeuser+<random_id>@test.local` via the registration API before Scenario A runs. This account is fully isolated — no shared state with other specs or runs.
- The test environment contains at least 6 existing donation listings (read-only seed data) so that scroll position can be meaningfully tested.
- Initial viewport is set to desktop width (e.g., 1280x800).

Teardown (after all scenarios, even on failure):
- Delete the per-run account created during setup and all records it owns.
- Do NOT delete shared read-only seed fixtures.

## Business Scenarios
- Scenario A (DB-1): User resizes from desktop to mobile — layout switches to single-column
- Scenario B (DB-2): User resizes from mobile back to desktop — layout switches to 3-column

## Actor Variants
- EQ-1 — User resizes from desktop (>768px) to mobile (<768px) while viewing the feed -> DB-1
- EQ-2 — User resizes from mobile (<768px) back to desktop (>768px) -> DB-2
- EQ-3 — User resizes across the breakpoint multiple times in quick succession (stress / debounce case) -> DB-1, DB-2

## Outcome Branches
- DB-1 -> Layout switches to single-column without a page reload (EQ-1, EQ-3)
- DB-2 -> Layout switches to 3-column without a page reload (EQ-2, EQ-3)

## Business Boundaries
- BV-1 (resize from 769px to 767px): crossing the breakpoint by minimum delta (2px), expect layout switch
- BV-2 (resize from 767px to 769px): crossing back by minimum delta (2px), expect layout switch back

## Acceptance Criteria
- AC1: When the user resizes from desktop to below mobile breakpoint, the layout switches from 3-column to single-column without a page reload (DB-1, EQ-1)
- AC2: When the user resizes from mobile back to desktop, the layout switches from single-column to 3-column without a page reload (DB-2, EQ-2)
- AC3: Scroll position is preserved after resizing across the breakpoint in both directions (DB-1, DB-2)
- AC4: Multiple rapid resizes across the breakpoint do not cause visual glitches or broken layout (EQ-3)
- AC5: At the minimum boundary crossing (769px -> 767px), layout transitions cleanly (BV-1)
- AC6: At the minimum boundary crossing back (767px -> 769px), layout transitions cleanly (BV-2)
- AC7: After resize, no full-page reload occurs — the URL and application state remain intact (ABSENT-1)
- AC8: After resize, scroll position is not lost (ABSENT-2)

## Absent Elements
- After resize: no full-page reload (URL and AngularJS state remain intact; no loading spinner for initial page load)
- After resize: scroll position not lost (content the user was viewing remains visible or near-visible)

## Steps

### Scenario A: Desktop to mobile resize
<!-- covers: DB-1, EQ-1, BV-1, ABSENT-1, ABSENT-2 -->
1. Log in as the test user on a desktop viewport (1280x800)
2. Navigate to the listing feed at $E2E_BASE_URL
3. Wait for the feed to load and verify cards are in 3-column grid
4. Scroll down so that some cards are visible below the initial viewport
5. Note the current scroll position and the content visible on screen
6. Resize the viewport to 767px width (crossing below the breakpoint)
7. Verify AC1: cards are now displayed in a single column
8. Verify AC7 (Absent): no full-page reload occurred — URL has not changed, no initial loading spinner appeared
9. Verify AC3/AC8 (Absent): scroll position is preserved — the same approximate content area is visible
10. Take a screenshot and save to $E2E_ARTIFACTS_DIR/resize-breakpoint/desktop-to-mobile.png

### Scenario A (boundary): Minimum delta crossing 769px to 767px
<!-- covers: BV-1 -->
11. Set viewport to exactly 769px, verify 3-column layout is active
12. Resize viewport to exactly 767px
13. Verify AC5: layout transitions to single-column cleanly at this 2px boundary crossing
14. Take a screenshot and save to $E2E_ARTIFACTS_DIR/resize-breakpoint/boundary-769-to-767.png

### Scenario B: Mobile to desktop resize
<!-- covers: DB-2, EQ-2, BV-2, ABSENT-1, ABSENT-2 -->
1. Starting from the mobile viewport (767px) from Scenario A
2. Note the current scroll position and visible content
3. Resize the viewport back to desktop width (1280px)
4. Verify AC2: cards are now displayed in a 3-column grid again
5. Verify AC7 (Absent): no full-page reload occurred
6. Verify AC3/AC8 (Absent): scroll position is preserved
7. Take a screenshot and save to $E2E_ARTIFACTS_DIR/resize-breakpoint/mobile-to-desktop.png

### Scenario B (boundary): Minimum delta crossing 767px to 769px
<!-- covers: BV-2 -->
8. Set viewport to exactly 767px, verify single-column layout
9. Resize viewport to exactly 769px
10. Verify AC6: layout transitions to 3-column cleanly at this 2px boundary crossing
11. Take a screenshot and save to $E2E_ARTIFACTS_DIR/resize-breakpoint/boundary-767-to-769.png

### Rapid resize stress test
<!-- covers: EQ-3 -->
1. Set viewport to desktop width (1280px), verify 3-column grid
2. Rapidly resize the viewport across the breakpoint multiple times (e.g., 1280 -> 600 -> 1280 -> 600 -> 1280) in quick succession
3. After the final resize to desktop, verify AC4: the 3-column grid is displayed correctly with no visual glitches or broken layout
4. Verify all cards are properly arranged without overlapping or misalignment
5. Take a screenshot and save to $E2E_ARTIFACTS_DIR/resize-breakpoint/rapid-resize-final.png

